RIP derived, O - OSPF derived,\n       C - connected, S - static, B - BGP derived,\n       * - candidate default route, IA - OSPF inter area route,\n       i - IS-IS derived, ia - IS-IS, U - per-user static route,\n       o - on-demand routing, M - mobile, P - periodic downloaded static route,\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, E1 - OSPF external type 1 route,\n       E2 - OSPF external type 2 route, N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1 route,\n       N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2 route\n\nGateway of last resort is 10.119.254.240 to network 10.140.0.0\n\nO E2 10.110.0.0 [160/5] via 10.119.254.6, 0:01:00, Ethernet2\nE    10.67.10.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nO E2 10.68.132.0 [160/5] via 10.119.254.6, 0:00:59, Ethernet2\nO E2 10.130.0.0 [160/5] via 10.119.254.6, 0:00:59, Ethernet2\nE    10.128.0.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.129.0.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.65.129.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.10.0.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.75.139.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:23, Ethernet2\nE    10.16.208.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.84.148.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:23, Ethernet2\nE    10.31.223.0 [200/128] via 10.119.254.244, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.44.236.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:23, Ethernet2\nE    10.141.0.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:22, Ethernet2\nE    10.140.0.0 [200/129] via 10.119.254.240, 0:02:23, Ethernet2\n</code></pre>\n', '2018-01-03 10:31:38', ''),
(7, 'Installation and first configuration steps', 5, '<style>\n  .imgs-wrapper{\n    display: flex;\n    flex-direction: row;\n    margin-bottom: 8px;\n  }\n  img {\n    flex-grow: 1;\n    margin: 2px;\n  }\n  a {\n    outline: none;\n  }\n</style>\n<!--<img src=\"../../../assets/images/00setup.png\" alt=\"Setup\">-->\n<p>Kali Loonix installed and first config steps</p>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    We will have Kali installed in a VirtualBox machine. One network interface will be in bridge mode with our laptop wireless card.\n    This will produce an Ethernet (wired) connection in the virtual machine. For the second interface, I have a USB wireless internet\n    card (Edimax EW-7811UTC) that I\'ll add to the machine and install there.\n\n    <div class=\"imgs-wrapper\">\n      <img src=\"../../../assets/images/0001.png\" alt=\"Wireless bridged\">\n      <img src=\"../../../assets/images/0002.png\" alt=\"USB wirelees card\">\n    </div>\n    <ul>\n      <li>\n        Remember to add your user to the <code>vboxusers</code> group in order for the USB devices to be shared.<sup><a href=\"#fn1\" id=\"ref1\">[1]</a></sup>\n      </li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>\n    Install the external wireless card in Kali.\n    <a href=\"https://ubuntuforums.org/showthread.php?t=2228244&p=13042921#post13042921\">This post</a>\n    has excelent guidance on how to do it\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>Verifying interface details. <code>eth0</code> comes from our wireless\n  interface in the laptop. It\'s bridged so it has an IP address on the same network as the host laptop.\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ifconfig</b>\neth0: flags=4163&lt;UP,BROADCAST,RUNNING,MULTICAST&gt;  mtu 1500\n        inet 192.168.43.163  netmask 255.255.255.0  broadcast 192.168.43.255\n        inet6 fe80::a00:27ff:fe44:ca8f  prefixlen 64  scopeid 0x20&lt;link&gt;\n        ether 08:00:27:44:ca:8f  txqueuelen 1000  (Ethernet)\n        RX packets 35  bytes 3186 (3.1 KiB)\n        RX errors 0  dropped 0  overruns 0  frame 0\n        TX packets 41  bytes 3439 (3.3 KiB)\n        TX errors 0  dropped 0 overruns 0  carrier 0  collisions 0\n\nlo: flags=73&lt;UP,LOOPBACK,RUNNING&gt;  mtu 65536\n        inet 127.0.0.1  netmask 255.0.0.0\n        inet6 ::1  prefixlen 128  scopeid 0x10&lt;host&gt;\n        loop  txqueuelen 1000  (Local Loopback)\n        RX packets 100  bytes 7596 (7.4 KiB)\n        RX errors 0  dropped 0  overruns 0  frame 0\n        TX packets 100  bytes 7596 (7.4 KiB)\n        TX errors 0  dropped 0 overruns 0  carrier 0  collisions 0\n\nwlan0: flags=4099&lt;UP,BROADCAST,MULTICAST&gt;  mtu 1500\n        ether 74:da:38:c9:9a:94  txqueuelen 1000  (Ethernet)\n        RX packets 0  bytes 0 (0.0 B)\n        RX errors 0  dropped 19  overruns 0  frame 0\n        TX packets 0  bytes 0 (0.0 B)\n        TX errors 0  dropped 0 overruns 0  carrier 0  collisions 0\n</pre>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>Wireless information. <code>iwconfig</code> shows our external wireless card, which for the moment\n    is not connected to any network.\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>iwconfig</b>\nwlan0     unassociated  Nickname:&quot;&lt;WIFI@REALTEK&gt;&quot;\n          Mode:Managed  Frequency=2.412 GHz  Access Point: Not-Associated\n          Sensitivity:0/0\n          Retry:off   RTS thr:off   Fragment thr:off\n          Encryption key:off\n          Power Management:off\n          Link Quality:0  Signal level:0  Noise level:0\n          Rx invalid nwid:0  Rx invalid crypt:0  Rx invalid frag:0\n          Tx excessive retries:0  Invalid misc:0   Missed beacon:0\n\nlo        no wireless extensions.\n\neth0      no wireless extensions.\n</pre>\n    <ul>\n        <li>\n          <code>Tx-Power</code> is the transmit power. In the US is limited to 27 dBm.\n        </li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>Setup support for ssh\n    <ul>\n      <li>Newer versions of Kali come with a pair public and private keys. If we want to change them, follow <a href =\"http://blog.7-a.org/2013/04/kali-linux-dude-wheres-my-sshd-generate.html\">\n      this blog post</a>.</li>\n      <li>Start the SSH service.\n      </li>\n    </ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>/etc/init.d/ssh start</b>\n[<font color=\"#4E9A06\"> ok </font>] Starting ssh (via systemctl): ssh.service.\n</pre>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li> If we want to configure a static IP address, with the command <code style=\"inline\">ifconfig</code>:\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ifconfig eth0 down</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ifconfig eth0 192.168.43.77/24 up</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>route add default gw 192.168.43.1</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ping 8.8.8.8</b>\nPING 8.8.8.8 (8.8.8.8) 56(84) bytes of data.\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=1 ttl=54 time=704 ms\n64 bytes from 8.8.8.8: icmp_seq=2 ttl=54 time=314 ms\n^C\n--- 8.8.8.8 ping statistics ---\n2 packets transmitted, 2 received, 0% packet loss, time 1001ms\nrtt min/avg/max/mdev = 314.192/509.300/704.409/195.109 ms\n</pre>\n    <ul>\n      <li>We need to configure a DNS server as well.</li>\n    </ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>cat /etc/resolv.conf</b>\n# Generated by NetworkManager\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ping google.es</b>\nping: google.es: Name or service not known\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>echo nameserver 8.8.8.8 &gt; /etc/resolv.conf</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ping google.es</b>\nPING google.es (216.58.204.3) 56(84) bytes of data.\n^C64 bytes from 216.58.204.3: icmp_seq=1 ttl=51 time=318 ms\n\n--- google.es ping statistics ---\n1 packets transmitted, 1 received, 0% packet loss, time 0ms\nrtt min/avg/max/mdev = 318.659/318.659/318.659/0.000 ms\n</pre>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>\n    If we want the changes to stay after rebooting we have to edit the file <code>/etc/network/interfaces</code> instead:\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>cat /etc/network/interfaces</b>\n# This file describes the network interfaces available on your system\n# and how to activate them. For more information, see interfaces(5).\n\nsource /etc/network/interfaces.d/*\n\n# The loopback network interface\nauto lo\niface lo inet loopback\n\n# Wired interface\nauto eth0\niface eth inet static\n  address 192.168.43.222\n  netmask 255.255.255.0\n  network 192.168.43.0\n  broadcast 192.168.43.255\n  gateway 192.168.43.1\n</pre>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>\n    If we want to keep our SSH settings after reboot (there is a similar command for the network settings but\n    its use is not recommended)\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>update-rc.d -f ssh defaults</b>\n</pre>\n  </li>\n  <br>\n  <li>\n    Configuring the wireless transmission Power\n    <ul>\n      <li>We can alter or manipulate the signal strength on the adapter in the Kali machine</li>\n      <li>\n        Depending on the country that you live in, there\'s very likely a regulatory agency that\'s controlling the airways\n        <sup><a href=\"#fn2\" id=\"ref2\">[2]</a></sup>\n      </li>\n      <li>In one terminal, we use the <code>tail</code> command to see in real time the changes to the log messages file:</li>\n    </ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>tail -f -n 0 /var/log/messages</b>\n</pre>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Instructions to change country code and transmission power:</li>\n    </ul>\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ifconfig wlan0 down</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>iw reg set US</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>iw reg get</b>\nglobal\ncountry US: DFS-FCC\n	(2402 - 2472 @ 40), (N/A, 30), (N/A)\n	(5170 - 5250 @ 80), (N/A, 23), (N/A), AUTO-BW\n	(5250 - 5330 @ 80), (N/A, 23), (0 ms), DFS, AUTO-BW\n	(5490 - 5730 @ 160), (N/A, 23), (0 ms), DFS\n	(5735 - 5835 @ 80), (N/A, 30), (N/A)\n	(57240 - 63720 @ 2160), (N/A, 40), (N/A)\n\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>iwconfig wlan0 channel 13</b>\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>iwconfig wlan0 txpower 23</b>\nError for wireless request &quot;Set Tx Power&quot; (8B26) :\n    SET failed on device wlan0 ; Operation not permitted.\n<font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>root@kali</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~</b></font># <b>ifconfig wlan0 up</b>\n</pre>\n    <ul>\n      <li>In this wireless card it doesn\'t work. Maybe because of the drivers.</li>\n      <li>System log messages doesn\'t show anything other than the interface up/down messages.</li>\n      <li>Setting the country code to BO or some other place allows for higher transmission power limits.</li>\n    </ul>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<br>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n  <li>\n    Remainder: useful commands\n    <table>\n      <thead>\n        <tr>\n          <th>Command</th>\n          <th>Description</th>\n        </tr>\n      </thead>\n      <tbody>\n        <tr>\n          <td>\n            <code class=\"inline\">/etc/init.d/networking start</code><br>\n            <code>service networking start</code><br>\n            <code>start networking</code>\n          </td>\n          <td>Enable / disable / restart networking service</td>\n        </tr>\n        <tr>\n          <td>\n            <code class=\"inline\">/etc/init.d/ssh start</code><br>\n          </td>\n          <td>Enable / disable / restart SSH service</td>\n        </tr>\n      </tbody>\n    </table>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<br>\n<hr>\n<sup id=\"fn1\">[1] <a href=\"https://askubuntu.com/questions/282018/wifi-card-on-an-virtualboxs-ubuntu\">https://askubuntu.com/questions/282018/wifi-card-on-an-virtualboxs-ubuntu</a> &nbsp; <a href=\"#ref1\" title=\"Jump back to footnote 1 in the text.\"></a></sup><br>\n<sup id=\"fn2\">[2] <a href=\"https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/wireless/wcs/3-2/configuration/guide/wcscfg32/wcscod.pdf\">https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/wireless/wcs/3-2/configuration/guide/wcscfg32/wcscod.pdf</a> [PDF] &nbsp; <a href=\"#ref2\" title=\"Jump back to footnote 2 in the text.\"></a></sup>\n', '2018-01-15 08:38:31', ''),
(8, 'Absolute minimum configuration for GNS3 devices', 1, '<style>\n</style>\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">For routers</h4>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">\nhostname R1\nno ip domain lookup\nline con 0\n exec-timeout 0 0\n logging synchronous\n exit\n!For interfaces connected to switches:\nint f0/0\n speed 100\n duplex full\ndo copy run start\n</pre>\n<br>\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">For switches</h4>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">\nhostname SW1\nno ip routing\nno ip domain lookup\nline con 0\n exec-timeout 0 0\n logging synchronous\n exit\n!For interfaces present on the EhterSwitch module that are\n! connected to other switches, routers or computers:\nint f1/0\n speed 100\n duplex full\ndo copy run start\n</pre>\n<br>\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">For computers</h4>\n<pre class=\"terminal\">\nhostname PC-A\nno ip routing\nno ip domain lookup\n!For interfaces that are connected to switches\ninterface FastEthernet0/0\n speed 100\n duplex full\nline con 0\n exec-timeout 0 0\n logging synchronous\ndo copy run start\n</pre>\n', '2018-01-20 16:54:06', ''),
(10, 'List of Cisco show commands', 1, '<style>\na.show-command {\n  margin-bottom: 0;\n  font-size: 1.1rem;\n  text-decoration: none;\n  display: inline-block;\n  /* Copied from bootstrap <code>*/\n  font-family: SFMono-Regular,Menlo,Monaco,Consolas,\"Liberation Mono\",\"Courier New\",monospace;\n  padding: .2rem .4rem;\n  color: #bd4147;\n  background-color: #f8f9fa;\n  border-radius: .25rem;\n}\nli.first-level {\n  font-size: 1.5rem;\n  margin-top: 15px;\n}\nli.first-level h4 {\n  margin: 0;\n}\n</style>\n<!--<img src=\"../../../assets/images/00setup.png\" alt=\"Setup\">-->\n<ul>\n  <li class=\"first-level\">\n    <h4>OSPF</h4>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-ip-protocols\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show ip protocols</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-ip-ospf\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show ip ospf</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-ip-ospf-interface\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show ip ospf interface [fa0/0]</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-ip-ospf-neighbor\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show ip ospf neighbor</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-ip-route\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show ip route</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#ospf-show-run-section-ospf\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show run | section ospf</b></code></a><br>\n  </li>\n  <li class=\"first-level\">\n    <h4>STP</h4>\n    <a href=\"#stp-show-cdp-neighbor\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show cdp neighbor</b></code></a><br>\n    <a href=\"#stp-show-spanning-tree\" class=\"show-command\"><code># <b>show spanning-tree</b></code></a><br>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<br><br>\n<h4>Examples</h4>\n<hr>\n<ul>\n  <li class=\"first-level\">\n    <h4>OSPF</h4>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-ip-protocols\" class=\"terminal\">Sock# <b>show ip protocols</b>\nRouting Protocol is \"ospf 1\"\n  Outgoing update filter list for all interfaces is not set\n  Incoming update filter list for all interfaces is not set\n  Router ID 3.3.3.3\n  Number of areas in this router is 1. 1 normal 0 stub 0 nssa\n  Maximum path: 4\n  Routing for Networks:\n    10.1.1.0 0.0.0.255 area 0\n    10.1.2.1 0.0.0.0 area 0\n Reference bandwidth unit is 100 mbps\n  Routing Information Sources:\n    Gateway         Distance      Last Update\n    3.3.3.3              110      00:02:04\n    4.4.4.4              110      00:02:27\n  Distance: (default is 110)\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-ip-ospf\" class=\"terminal\">Shoe# <b>show ip ospf</b>\n Routing Process \"ospf 1\" with ID 4.4.4.4\n Start time: 00:00:06.792, Time elapsed: 04:33:33.564\n Supports only single TOS(TOS0) routes\n Supports opaque LSA\n Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n Supports area transit capability\n Router is not originating router-LSAs with maximum metric\n Initial SPF schedule delay 5000 msecs\n Minimum hold time between two consecutive SPFs 10000 msecs\n Maximum wait time between two consecutive SPFs 10000 msecs\n Incremental-SPF disabledSock# show ip ospf interface se1/0\nSerial1/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.2.1/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 3.3.3.3, Network Type POINT_TO_POINT, Cost: 6476\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State POINT_TO_POINT\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 1, Dead 4, Wait 4, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    Hello due in 00:00:00\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 2/2, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 1, maximum is 2\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 4 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 1, Adjacent neighbor count is 1\n    Adjacent with neighbor 4.4.4.4\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\n Minimum LSA interval 5 secs\n Minimum LSA arrival 1000 msecs\n LSA group pacing timer 240 secs\n Interface flood pacing timer 33 msecs\n Retransmission pacing timer 66 msecs\n Number of external LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x000000\n Number of opaque AS LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x000000\n Number of DCbitless external and opaque AS LSA 0\n Number of DoNotAge external and opaque AS LSA 0\n Number of areas in this router is 1. 1 normal 0 stub 0 nssa\n Number of areas transit capable is 0\n External flood list length 0\n IETF NSF helper support enabled\n Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n    Area BACKBONE(0)\n	Number of interfaces in this area is 2\n	Area has no authentication\n	SPF algorithm last executed 00:08:24.624 ago\n	SPF algorithm executed 14 times\n	Area ranges are\n	Number of LSA 5. Checksum Sum 0x01EAC4\n	Number of opaque link LSA 0. Checksum Sum 0x000000\n	Number of DCbitless LSA 0\n	Number of indication LSA 0\n	Number of DoNotAge LSA 0\n	Flood list length 0\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-ip-ospf-interface\" class=\"terminal\">Shoe# <b>show ip ospf interface f0/0</b>\nFastEthernet0/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.3.1/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 4.4.4.4, Network Type BROADCAST, Cost: 5\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State DR, Priority 1\n  Designated Router (ID) 4.4.4.4, Interface address 10.1.3.1\n  No backup designated router on this network\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 10, Dead 40, Wait 40, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    No Hellos (Passive interface)\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 2/2, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 0, maximum is 0\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 0 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 0, Adjacent neighbor count is 0\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\n\nSock# <b>show ip ospf interface se1/0</b>\nSerial1/0 is up, line protocol is up\n  Internet Address 10.1.2.1/24, Area 0\n  Process ID 1, Router ID 3.3.3.3, Network Type POINT_TO_POINT, Cost: 6476\n  Transmit Delay is 1 sec, State POINT_TO_POINT\n  Timer intervals configured, Hello 1, Dead 4, Wait 4, Retransmit 5\n    oob-resync timeout 40\n    Hello due in 00:00:00\n  Supports Link-local Signaling (LLS)\n  Cisco NSF helper support enabled\n  IETF NSF helper support enabled\n  Index 2/2, flood queue length 0\n  Next 0x0(0)/0x0(0)\n  Last flood scan length is 1, maximum is 2\n  Last flood scan time is 0 msec, maximum is 4 msec\n  Neighbor Count is 1, Adjacent neighbor count is 1\n    Adjacent with neighbor 4.4.4.4\n  Suppress hello for 0 neighbor(s)\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-ip-ospf-neighbor\" class=\"terminal\">Sock# <b>sh ip ospf neighbor</b>\nNeighbor ID     Pri   State           Dead Time   Address         Interface\n4.4.4.4           0   FULL/  -        00:00:32    10.1.2.2        Serial1/0\n1.1.1.1          10   FULL/DR         00:00:38    10.1.1.1        FastEthernet0/0\n2.2.2.2           1   FULL/DROTHER    00:00:38    10.1.1.2        FastEthernet0/0\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-ip-route\" class=\"terminal\">Tie# <b>sh ip route</b>\nCodes: C - connected, S - static, R - RIP, M - mobile, B - BGP\n       D - EIGRP, EX - EIGRP external, O - OSPF, IA - OSPF inter area\n       N1 - OSPF NSSA external type 1, N2 - OSPF NSSA external type 2\n       E1 - OSPF external type 1, E2 - OSPF external type 2\n       i - IS-IS, su - IS-IS summary, L1 - IS-IS level-1, L2 - IS-IS level-2\n       ia - IS-IS inter area, * - candidate default, U - per-user static route\n       o - ODR, P - periodic downloaded static route\n\nGateway of last resort is 10.0.0.2 to network 0.0.0.0\n\n     10.0.0.0/8 is variably subnetted, 10 subnets, 2 masks\nO       10.2.0.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:21, Serial1/0\nO       10.2.0.0/21 is a summary, 00:18:21, Null0\nC       10.2.1.0/24 is directly connected, Serial1/0\nO       10.2.2.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:21, Serial1/0\nC       10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, FastEthernet0/0\nO       10.2.3.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:21, Serial1/0\nO IA    10.1.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.2, 00:18:21, FastEthernet0/0\nO       10.2.4.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:22, Serial1/0\nO       10.2.5.0/24 [110/65] via 10.2.1.2, 00:18:22, Serial1/0\nO IA    10.51.0.0/21 [110/65] via 10.0.0.3, 00:17:44, FastEthernet0/0\nO*E2 0.0.0.0/0 [110/1] via 10.0.0.2, 00:01:34, FastEthernet0/0\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"ospf-show-run-section-ospf\" class=\"terminal\">\n</pre>\n<br>\n<ul>\n  <li class=\"first-level\">\n    <h4>STP</h4>\n  </li>\n</ul>\n<pre id=\"stp-show-cdp-neighbor\" class=\"terminal\">S1# <b>show cdp neighbor</b>\nCapability Codes: R - Router, T - Trans Bridge, B - Source Route Bridge\n                  S - Switch, H - Host, I - IGMP, r - Repeater\n\nDevice ID        Local Intrfce     Holdtme    Capability  Platform  Port ID\nS3               Fas 1/3            176          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\nS2               Fas 1/2            152          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\nS5               Fas 1/5            127          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\nS4               Fas 1/4            173          S I      3725      Fas 1/0\n</pre>\n<pre id=\"stp-show-spanning-tree\" class=\"terminal\">! On a real switch we would see port role as well (Root/Desg/Altn)\nS1# <b>show spanning-tree</b>\nVLAN1\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\n  Root ID    Priority    32768\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\n             Cost        19\n             Port        46 (FastEthernet1/5)\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\n\n  Bridge ID  Priority    32768\n             Address     c207.0961.0000\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\n             Aging Time 300\n\nInterface                                   Designated\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\nFastEthernet1/2      128.43   128    19 BLK    19 32768 c206.0961.0000 128.41\nFastEthernet1/3      128.44   128    19 FWD    19 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.44\nFastEthernet1/4      128.45   128    19 FWD    19 32768 c207.0961.0000 128.45\nFastEthernet1/5      128.46   128    19 FWD     0 32768 c205.0971.0000 128.41\n\n\nS5# <b>show spanning-tree</b>\nVLAN1\n  Spanning tree enabled protocol ieee\n  Root ID    Priority    32768\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\n             This bridge is the root\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\n\n  Bridge ID  Priority    32768\n             Address     c205.0971.0000\n             Hello Time   2 sec  Max Age 20 sec  Forward Delay 15 sec\n             Aging Time 300\n\nInterface                                   Designated\nName                 Port ID Prio Cost  Sts Cost  Bridge ID            Port ID\n-------------------- ------- ---- ----- --- ----- -------------------- -------\nFastEthernet1/0      128.41   128    19 FWD     0 32768 c205.0971.0000 128.41\nFastEthernet1/1      128.42   128    19 FWD     0 32768 c205.0971.0000 128.42\n</pre>\n<br>\n', '2018-01-21 17:09:20', 'Cisco show commands outputs taken from real devices. This list will keep growing as I continue studying.'),
(14, 'Git essentials', 7, '<style>\r\n</style>\r\n<!--<img src=\"../../../assets/images/00setup.png\" alt=\"Setup\">-->\r\n<h4 class=\"subtitle\">Basic workflow</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Clone the repo\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest</b></font>$ git clone https://cyberFELIX@bitbucket.org/cyberFELIX/felix-test-repo.git\r\nCloning into &apos;felix-test-repo&apos;...\r\nPassword for &apos;https://cyberFELIX@bitbucket.org&apos;:\r\nremote: Counting objects: 3, done.\r\nremote: Compressing objects: 100% (2/2), done.\r\nremote: Total 3 (delta 0), reused 0 (delta 0)\r\nUnpacking objects: 100% (3/3), done.\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Add a new file and check the status of the repository\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git status\r\nOn branch master\r\nYour branch is up to date with &apos;origin/master&apos;.\r\n\r\nUntracked files:\r\n  (use &quot;git add &lt;file&gt;...&quot; to include in what will be committed)\r\n\r\n	<font color=\"#CC0000\">index.js</font>\r\n\r\nnothing added to commit but untracked files present (use &quot;git add&quot; to track)\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Send the new file to the staging area\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git add .\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Modify the file and show differences between the staging area and\r\n    the working directory\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ echo &quot;var newVar = 7&quot; &gt;&gt; index.js\r\n<font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git diff\r\n<b>diff --git a/index.js b/index.js</b>\r\n<b>index 7921bd9..ea3cfaf 100644</b>\r\n<b>--- a/index.js</b>\r\n<b>+++ b/index.js</b>\r\n<font color=\"#06989A\">@@ -1 +1,2 @@</font>\r\n var hola = &apos;hello&apos;\r\n<font color=\"#4E9A06\">+var newVar = 7</font>\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Commit: permanently store the changes from the staging area inside the\r\n    repository.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git add .\r\n<font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git commit -m &quot;First modifications&quot;\r\n[master c48a54d] First modifications\r\n 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+)\r\n create mode 100644 index.js\r\n</pre>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>\r\n    See the list of commits.\r\n  </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<pre class=\"terminal\"><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>user@ubuntupc</b></font>:<font color=\"#3465A4\"><b>~/GitTest/felix-test-repo</b></font>$ git log\r\n<font color=\"#C4A000\">commit c48a54d89b2ff4310ff4d41fb8d3bd85daa54b6e (</font><font color=\"#06989A\"><b>HEAD -&gt; </b></font><font color=\"#4E9A06\"><b>master</b></font><font color=\"#C4A000\">)</font>\r\nAuthor: d-silvas &lt;d.silvas@outlook.com&gt;\r\nDate:   Fri Feb 2 12:56:00 2018 +0000\r\n\r\n    First modifications\r\n\r\n<font color=\"#C4A000\">commit 36d6a86a64ee49ba6e10b3e6a5360006a5ff93dd (</font><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>origin/master</b></font><font color=\"#C4A000\">, </font><font color=\"#CC0000\"><b>origin/HEAD</b></font><font color=\"#C4A000\">)</font>\r\nAuthor: David Silva &lt;felix@cyberratss.london&gt;\r\nDate:   Fri Feb 2 12:33:57 2018 +0000\r\n\r\n    README.md created online with Bitbucket\r\n</pre>\r\n', '2018-02-03 22:34:25', 'A few very basic operations to get started with Git.'),
